Strike a Rock, a documentary about members of the Marikana-based Sikhala Sonke organisation, puts you fleetingly into the thick of the women’s lowly struggle for dignity in that mining town. Theirs, without arms or brute strength, was unlikely to make the news, except for a singular event — when ANC proportional representation councillor Pauline Masutlhe was gunned down by police during one of the many post-Marikana massacre crackdown raids in Nkaneng. That tragic incident probably galvanised the women’s movement, already strengthened by the collective pain many of them shared during the lead-up to and after the Marikana massacre. The film follows two main protagonists, Primrose Sonti and Thumeka Magwangqana, two friends hemmed in by the industrial and human borders of Lonmin.
 
